<div id="review_3218706887" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3218706887" />
    <a title="Flo Renzen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/110937801-flo-renzen"><img alt="Flo Renzen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3218706887?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Flo Renzen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Flo Renzen" href="/user/show/110937801-flo-renzen">Flo Renzen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/51475154-monogamy-book-one-lover">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3218706887" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5004613682759682174">Dear Victoria Sobolev, I realize the entire series has not yet been published but I wanted to review at least on book 1 already. I read your “Monogamy”, book 1 by accident. I felt attracted to your book by its name as “monogamy” to me sounded rather moral and in a way boring but the book cover looked so totally different than that - it promised there would be passion maybe going to the limit in there. Apart from that, I had no expectations at all. Now I am surprised to say “Monogamy” made me fee</span>
  <span id="freeText5004613682759682174" style="display:none">Dear Victoria Sobolev, I realize the entire series has not yet been published but I wanted to review at least on book 1 already. I read your “Monogamy”, book 1 by accident. I felt attracted to your book by its name as “monogamy” to me sounded rather moral and in a way boring but the book cover looked so totally different than that - it promised there would be passion maybe going to the limit in there. Apart from that, I had no expectations at all. Now I am surprised to say “Monogamy” made me feel somewhat different and new about love and faith and discover new aspects of lust and sexuality. Now at the point I finished book 1 this novel makes me think a lot. The painful – but also a bit hopeful? we’ll see – cut at book 1 leaves me excited and desperate for what will be happening next.<br />I was rewarded – there IS indeed a lot of passion and love and (true) heartache and pain in there already (saying this with a light shiver and a twinkle at the coming book 2). The part on “doing the wrong things feeling just so good it must be right” was beautiful and painful at a time. The part on leaving everything behind for selfless care and, let’s face it, sacrifice yourself for your beloved one touched me deeply. Apart from speaking of incredible love and passion, “Monogamy” speaks of “really serious things in life” and offers deep psychological insights without being boring. In fact, sometimes I felt like reading a psychological crime novel, the difference being that instead of “who did it” the suspense was/is all about “what might he/she/they be REALLY feeling”. It sometimes felt like there had to be more behind the obvious and the “clues” made me try to read between the lines and make up my own theory of what is actually going on and what it all will turn down to. Anxious to learn whether I’m right! <br />I think, Victoria Sobolev elaborated thoroughly on the protagonists, Alex and Lera, though they do not feel “artificial” - quite the opposite, to me, they feel genuine. From what I already know of them, they are genuine and logical in what they feel, how they act and why they act this way and not the other. And there is even more to that - they are inspiring. I feel their feelings for each other must be so unique one would not find feelings of that strength elsewhere. Alex and Lera seem to be strong and weak at a time, smart but at times also a bit stupid, good and somewhat a little bad maybe. And they are human. Their mistakes, their occasional “little badness” or “stupidity” and their bigger or smaller psychological issues made me sympathize with them and, in parts, reminded me of myself and real life and what I have experienced in it. It felt good to go along with them in their learning process which I suppose has just begun. <br />Of course, there is some fairy tale shining through in “Monogamy” but one you do not want to end. The fairy tale feeling is partly based on the beautiful language of Victoria Sobolev. Her language is vivid and rich, sometimes contemplative and sometimes passionate. It is intriguing but clear and straight where necessary and always far from primitive. But it’s not only the language: it’s the mood. I read this book and was in a certain mood of – what? It is hard to explain with just one word. It’s a mood of dreaming, despair, longing, struggling, hoping and sometimes close to crying. And wanting to learn more.<br />Reading “Monogamy”, book 1, was a pleasure, sometimes sweet and sometimes painful. Waiting for the English version of book 2 to come!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5004613682759682174" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

